<font color="#FF0000">SPOKES FROM THE WHEEL OF NAM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Mar  5 21:01:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Maya Lin's openning line about this site is great. I am stealing it and changing it to this:<br><br>
I want to pose questions for people to think about without telling them how to think, or why.  <br><br>
That's what keeps pulling me back here.  Picture this if you will.  The war was a bad tire and we all know that. We don't need to keep up with that round and round theme.  We all represent different spokes (i.e. a bicycle wheel comes to mind) that lead to the hub. I see the hub as a healing, a place of recognitizion, enlightenment, and healing.  First we have to know that there are many, many, other spokes, from the veteran, the jungle fighter, the tunnel rats, to the clerks, the pilots, the boat drivers, the resistors, the college boys, those who went to Canada with a moral resolution, and those with no morals an no resolution, those who protested and risked prison, those who hid behind their votes and high lottery numbers, we all are spokes on this wheel.<br><br>
It's so easy to get caught up in the tire, the rotten rubber, and post about whether its a communist tire or a god damn nixon tire, etc.  We can't change the tire, but we sure as hell can affect the hub.  <br><br>
I see a great debate raging on #6 about communism and I wonder why. Communism is gone, we are still here. I know that some of you out there are afraid to be honest, emotionally or intellectually, and hide behind false identities.  That's your choice I guess. I don't like it, but I can live with it.  Some of you prefer nicknames from the war, Good for you. You earned em.<br><br>
Perhaps when all the spokes know about each other, we can make sure they never hang a bad tire on our &quot;wheel&quot; again.<br><br>
Thanks to you all, posters and e-mailers, you brighten up my day.<br><br>
Barry
